# Gitignored files copied into each new worktree (`claude --worktree`, parallel
# desktop sessions, subagent worktrees). Gitignore syntax; a pattern only copies
# a file that is ALSO gitignored, so nothing tracked is ever duplicated.
#
# A worktree is a fresh checkout, so it starts without the local-only files that
# make this repo runnable. List only what something actually reads and what the
# worktree cannot regenerate for itself.

# The model endpoint for the live tiers: MODEL_PROTOCOL / MODEL_BASE_URL /
# MODEL_API_KEY / MODEL_ID. internal/modeltest opens this from the *repo root*,
# which inside a worktree is the worktree's own root (it resolves the path from
# its own source file), so an uncopied .env is simply absent rather than
# inherited from the main checkout. It has to be here because the opt-in
# contract is deliberately fail-closed: `make test` still passes without it (no
# consent variable, no paid call), but opting in with RUN_LIVE_MODEL_TESTS=1 or
# RUN_EVALS=1 then FAILS rather than skips — a missing endpoint must never look
# like a green build. So a worktree without this file looks perfectly healthy
# right up until you ask it to reach a model.
.env

# A filled-in copy of model-providers.example.json, mounted by the compose stack
# when MODEL_PROVIDERS_FILE names it (deploy/compose/README.md). Same class as
# .env: gitignored precisely because it carries a live api_key, and
# unrecoverable by the worktree. No leading slash, so it is covered wherever it
# is created — deploy/compose/model-providers.json included. (Helm does not read
# this file; its secret key of the same name is templated from Helm values.)
model-providers.json

# Not listed, deliberately:
#   go.work / go.work.sum — a workspace file's `use` paths are relative, so a
#     copy would resolve them against the worktree and point at the wrong
#     modules. Worse than absent.
#   coverage.out, *.test, /bin, .impeccable/ — build output and caches. `make
#     verify` regenerates them; a stale copy is a lie about what was run.
#   .claude/scheduled_tasks.lock — a lock. Copying one into a second working
#     directory is how you get two owners of the same lease.
#   .claude/settings.local.json and the rest of .claude/ — not this file's
#     business. Claude Code carries its own project configuration into a
#     worktree; verified by probe that settings.local.json lands there with no
#     pattern for it here.
